# Mayra Agent Safety Contracts

Model output is hostile input. Every action the model proposes is validated, classified, possibly approved by the user, logged, and only then executed. There is no path from a model response to an `agent-browser` command that skips this pipeline.

## Action Schema (v1)

- Allowed action types: `click`, `type`, `scroll`, `wait`, `navigate`. Anything else is rejected at validation time, including: `eval`, `download`, `upload`, `cookies`, `storage`, `network`, `clipboard`, `keyboard inserttext`, `mouse *`, `set headers`, `set credentials`, `addinitscript`.
- Required fields on every action: `action`, `target_ref`, `value`, `risk`, `reason`. Missing or extra fields fail validation (`extra='forbid'` on the Pydantic model).
- `target_ref` is either an `agent-browser` ref (`@e\d+`) from the most recent snapshot, or one of the constrained semantic locators (`role:button[name=...]`, `text:...`, `label:...`). Raw CSS selectors and XPath are rejected.
- `value` is `null` for actions that don't need it (`click`, `wait` with selector). For `type`/`navigate` it is a string ≤ 2048 chars and is redacted before logging if the target ref points to a password/secret field (detected via the accessibility tree).
- `risk` ∈ {`low`, `medium`, `high`}. Model-provided risk is advisory; the orchestrator re-classifies and uses the **max** of model-suggested and policy-classified risk.
- `reason` is free-form ≤ 280 chars, shown verbatim in the action log card.

The schema lives in `packages/contracts/actions.schema.json`. Pydantic models in Python and TS types in the UI are generated from it. Both load the same fixtures in tests.

## Validation Pipeline

1. Parse model output (chat reply + JSON action block). On JSON parse failure or schema failure, send **one** repair message ("your previous response did not validate against the action schema; resend valid JSON only"). On second failure, abort the task with `BudgetExhaustedError(reason='repair_budget')`.
2. Verify the ref exists in the latest snapshot (taken ≤ 1 action ago). If not, force a re-snapshot before retrying.
3. Re-classify risk (see below). Promote risk if needed.
4. If `risk == 'high'`, gate on user approval. If `risk in {'low','medium'}` and the action is not in a forced-confirm category, execute.

## Risk Classification (orchestrator, not the model)

Mark as `high` if any of the following hold:

- Target element text or accessible name contains (case-insensitive): `delete`, `remove`, `pay`, `purchase`, `checkout`, `confirm`, `submit`, `save changes`, `transfer`, `send money`, `disable`, `deactivate`.
- Action would submit a form on a domain matching a configurable sensitive-domain list (banking, payments, account settings paths).
- Target ref maps to an `input[type=file]`, `input[type=password]` (typing into), or a button inside a `<form>` whose action handles money/account changes.
- Action is `navigate` to a domain not on `--allowed-domains` for the task.
- Snapshot freshness is stale (page changed since last snapshot and the orchestrator hasn't reconciled).
- Model emitted any `agent-browser` capability we deny by default (eval, download, upload, clipboard, cookies, storage, network route, init script).

When in doubt, classify high. False positives cost a click; false negatives cost the user's bank account.

## Human-In-The-Loop (HITL)

- High-risk actions block the agent loop and emit an `approval_request` SSE event with: the action payload (value-redacted if sensitive), the annotated screenshot (numbered ref labels), and the natural-language reason.
- The UI surfaces a modal with the annotated screenshot, the action description, and **Approve / Reject** buttons. Approval requires an explicit click; no "remember this choice" for high-risk categories.
- 2FA / OTP screens: detect by accessibility role + input pattern (`role=textbox name~="code|otp|verification"`). Pause the loop, fire a Tauri desktop notification, post a `system_status` message. Never ask the model to invent or recall an OTP.
- Manual takeover: if the user interacts with the managed Chrome window mid-task, pause, re-snapshot, and require explicit resume unless the new snapshot's DOM fingerprint matches the previous one (then auto-resume after a 30-second idle).

## Budgets & Limits (enforced server-side)

- Per-task step budget: 25–40 (configurable per benchmark). Each model call counts as one step regardless of retries.
- Per-step repair budget: 1 (one repair attempt for malformed JSON, then abort).
- Per-step action retry budget: 2 (e.g. ref disappeared, re-snapshot and try again).
- Global model throttle: 10–12 req/min default, per-provider semaphore matching free-tier limits. Use a token-bucket limiter so bursts don't break the limit.
- Budget exhaustion ends the task cleanly with a `system_status` message; it does not crash the loop.

## Hard Abort

- The `/v1/tasks/{id}/abort` endpoint cancels the asyncio task immediately. The browser adapter must have a synchronous "stop" that interrupts any pending CDP command on the next event-loop tick.
- Abort is idempotent: calling abort on an already-cancelled or completed task returns 200 with the final status.

## Translating Validated Actions to `agent-browser`

- One pure function: `to_agent_browser_command(action: Action) -> list[str]`. No string interpolation of model output into shell commands.
- Allowed mappings (v1 only): `click @e3` ← `Action(action='click', target_ref='@e3')`; `fill @e7 "<value>"` ← `Action(action='type', target_ref='@e7', value=...)`; `scroll <dir> <px>` ← `Action(action='scroll', value='down:400')`; `wait <selector|ms>` ← `Action(action='wait', target_ref='@e2')`; `navigate <url>` ← `Action(action='navigate', value='https://...')` only when domain matches `--allowed-domains`.
- Execute via `agent-browser` with `--json --session $task_id`. Parse the JSON result. On non-2xx exit or `error` key in JSON, surface as `BrowserError`.
- Never pass `--no-auto-dialog`, never invoke `chat`, never call `eval`, never enable `network route`/`storage *`/`cookies set` from model output.

## Logging, Audit, Privacy

- Every step emits a structured log: `{ correlation_id, task_id, step, observation_hash, intended_action, executed_action, result, latency_ms, provider, model, retries }`. The intended/executed distinction matters for the thesis evaluation.
- Redaction rules applied **before** any UI render or Supabase write:
  - API keys, bearer tokens, anything matching `^sk-|^sb_secret_|^[A-Za-z0-9_-]{40,}$` heuristically.
  - Password field values (always redacted to `"[REDACTED]"`).
  - OTP/2FA codes (always redacted).
  - Cookie/Authorization headers from any HAR/network output.
- Logs are append-only. The orchestrator never edits a previous log row. Corrections are new rows with a `corrects_step` reference.
- Memory: session-bound only for v1. No vector store, no cross-task memory. The orchestrator clears session state on task completion or user "new chat".

## AI-Prone Mistakes To Reject

- Trusting the model's `risk` field without re-classification.
- Accepting a CSS selector or XPath from model output instead of the ref/locator schema.
- Skipping snapshot freshness checks ("the ref was valid 5 actions ago, it's probably fine").
- Letting a `KeyError` or `JSONDecodeError` from model parsing become a 500 — wrap it in a repair-or-abort path.
- Logging the full request/response body of the model call without redaction.
- Adding new actions (`eval`, `download`, etc.) to v1 because "the model needs them" — extend the schema deliberately, with risk rules, in a new contracts version.
- Implementing approval as a UI-only check — it must be enforced in the orchestrator so a compromised UI bundle cannot bypass it.

